<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF/Disney Cruise Course a Hit at Rosen College of Hospitality Management</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Zenaida Gonzalez Kotala
		
		<span class="date">March 26, 2007</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1147/en_US/070320crueseman.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Courtesy of Scott Lee, Rosen College</p>
			
			<p>Twenty-one students from the Rosen College of Hospitality Management took a Disney cruise as the culmination of a cruise line management course they took this past semester. They visited a variety of places on the Disney Magic, including the engine room.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004102c4c1d99011146fc1c32007cca">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto: amcmeel@mail.ucf.edu">Ashley McMeel</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-903-8289</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.hospitality.ucf.edu/">Rosen College of Hospitality Management</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>ItÂ’s like no other class at the University of Central Florida.</p><p>Twenty-one students in the Rosen College of Hospitality Management returned from a cruise to the Bahamas on March 19 with a new appreciation for how a ship is run. The spring break trip (March 10-18) aboard DisneyÂ’s Magic was the culmination of a semesterÂ’s worth of class time learning about the cruise line industry.</p><p>Â“It was incredible,Â” said Danielle Thomas, who is scheduled to graduate in May with a bachelorÂ’s degree in hospitality management. Â“We had plenty of time to hang around the pool, but every day we had several hours of tours and talked to everyone from the ship captain to the performers.Â”</p><p>Disney Cruise Line President Tom McAlpin taught the class with the help of Assistant Professor Scott Lee. Lee, who accompanied the students on the seven-day trip, said some of the students have decided to pursue careers in the cruise line industry after completing the course.</p><p>The cruise line management course was the brainchild of McAlpin and Rosen College Dean Abe Pizam. McAlpin serves on RosenÂ’s advisory council and began talking about the possibility a few years ago.</p><p>In addition to McAlpin, about 50 Disney employees from a variety of departments give students instructions on every aspect of running a cruise line from planning the itineraries to hiring an international crew. </p><p>Â“ItÂ’s been an amazing course,Â” Lee said. Â“WeÂ’ve never had a course quite like this where there has been so much interaction with the industry. The partnership with Disney has been incredible. Disney really came through for our students in a powerful way.Â”</p><p>Students said they saw every part of the ship from the engine room to the crew cabins. They also participated in childrenÂ’s activities aboard the ship such as making magical cookies and playing pirates. McAlpin even treated all 21 students to a swim with stingrays during a stop on Castaway Cay Â– DisneyÂ’s private island.</p><p>Â“IÂ’d been on a lot of cruises before, but I had no idea what all went into making it such a perfect experience for guests,Â” Thomas said. Â“We got a 360-degree view of everything, and I have a whole newfound respect for them.Â”</p><p>Ashley Vance, a 19-year-old majoring in event planning, concurs.</p><p>She said she was most impressed by the honesty of the staff, who described some of the challenges that arenÂ’t covered in textbooks. For example, crew members discussed what it was like to be in the ocean for six months at a time, away from family, Vance said. </p><p>Â“They actually sat down with us and had frank discussions,Â” Vance said. Â“That was simply amazing.Â”</p><p>Professor Lee said the trip helped connect what students learned in the classroom to real life. He anticipates a bigger demand for the course next year when it will be expanded to the Cocoa campus.</p><p>Â“I think they realize what a rare opportunity this is,Â” Lee said. Â“Next year itÂ’s going to be really hard to get into the class, because students are spreading the word about this course fast.Â”</p>
		
	
